# Three layers of theme fade

After the CSS-variables migration, dark/light fading is owned by three
layers, each with a distinct job. They compose; do not conflate them:

1. **View Transitions API** for the page-wide toggle. One GPU
   cross-fade between a pre-flip and post-flip snapshot of the entire
   page, in place of N concurrent per-element CSS `transition`s.
2. **`PALETTE_TRANSITION` per-element CSS `transition`** for the
   fallback path (browsers without View Transitions support) and for
   non-toggle palette changes (focus / hover state, route navigation
   that mounts new palette-driven elements).
3. **SVG cross-fade** for imperative-DOM libraries (mermaid) whose
   rendered output is not CSS-animatable across re-renders.

A theme toggle on a supporting browser uses (1). The same toggle on
an unsupported browser uses (2). Both code paths use (3) for the
mermaid surfaces. The three sections below cover each in turn.

# Canonical transition token

The single source of truth for the per-element fade is the
`PALETTE_TRANSITION` constant exported from
`frontend/src/theme/transitions.js`. The duration, curve, and the
exact set of properties that get animated are each exported as
separate constants so a CSS keyframe `animation: ...` shorthand (used
where the `transition` shorthand is wrong because the property change
happens on first paint, not later â€” see "SVG content cross-fade"
below) can compose them without re-typing the literal, and so a
future palette-driven property can be added by appending one entry
to the property list:

```js
export const PALETTE_TRANSITION_DURATION = '0.2s';
export const PALETTE_TRANSITION_CURVE = 'cubic-bezier(.17,.67,.83,.67)';

export const PALETTE_TRANSITION_PROPERTIES = Object.freeze([
  'background-color', 'color', 'border-color',
  'fill', 'stroke', 'box-shadow',
]);

export const PALETTE_TRANSITION = PALETTE_TRANSITION_PROPERTIES
  .map((prop) => `${prop} ${PALETTE_TRANSITION_DURATION} ${PALETTE_TRANSITION_CURVE}`)
  .join(', ');
```

The composed `PALETTE_TRANSITION` is a property-list shorthand, not
the `'all 0.2s ...'` form that originally landed with this token. The
narrowing exists for two reasons:

1. **Performance.** `'all'` keeps a transition entry per element per
   CSS property, and on a long chat-detail page the `transition`
   override is applied to hundreds of MUI elements. The property
   list keeps entries only for the properties we actually animate,
   which measurably reduces compositor cost during the 200ms fade
   window.
2. **Defensive scope.** `'all'` would silently animate a future
   `width` / `height` change introduced by an unrelated refactor,
   which is almost never the author's intent on a theme-fade
   element. Listing properties keeps the blast radius explicit and
   grep-able.

Each property in the list earns its slot from at least one canonical
site: `background-color` for every `Paper` / `Card` / `body`; `color`
for every text-bearing element whose default flips between dark and
light; `border-color` for `Divider` and `'divider'`-token consumers
(`MessageImageGallery` thumbnails); `fill` and `stroke` for the
standalone `MuiSvgIcon` instances tinted by
`var(--mui-palette-highlight-main)`; `box-shadow` for `MuiCard` /
`MuiPaper` hover shadows. Add a new property to the array when
introducing a new animated palette-driven property â€” never inline a
one-off `transition` literal on the consuming element.

`transform` is intentionally NOT in the list. The only site that
animates a `transform` for a theme-fade-adjacent reason is
`ChatCard`'s `translateY(-8px)` hover-lift, which is a per-card
hover affordance rather than a palette change. Including it would
instantiate a `transform` transition entry on every `MuiCard` /
`MuiPaper` / `MuiAvatar` / `MuiTypography` / `MuiIconButton` /
`MuiChip` purely to support one card's hover. The hover-lift is
instead a local `transition` on `ChatCard`'s `Card` `sx`, composed
from `PALETTE_TRANSITION` plus an extra `transform` entry:

```js
import {
  PALETTE_TRANSITION,
  PALETTE_TRANSITION_CURVE,
  PALETTE_TRANSITION_DURATION,
} from '../../theme/transitions';

transition: `${PALETTE_TRANSITION}, transform ${PALETTE_TRANSITION_DURATION} ${PALETTE_TRANSITION_CURVE}`,
```

Per-element non-palette transitions (additional properties beyond
the centralized list) belong in the consuming component's `sx`
composed with `PALETTE_TRANSITION`, never inlined as their own
standalone `transition` shorthand that loses the centralized
properties.

Do not hardcode any of these literals anywhere else in the JS/JSX
tree. Curve and duration drift across sites is exactly the
inconsistency the tokens exist to prevent: `ProjectGroup` shipped
`'all 0.3s ease-in-out'` while `ChatCard` shipped
`'all 0.3s cubic-bezier(...)'` before this rule landed, and they
were unified on the cubic-bezier curve in the same refactor that
introduced the constant.

# View Transitions API for the page-wide toggle

The toggle in `App.js::ThemeModeBridge::toggleDarkMode` wraps
`useColorScheme().setMode(...)` in `document.startViewTransition`
plus `flushSync` from `react-dom`:

```js
const toggleDarkMode = () => {
  const next = !darkMode;
  const nextMode = next ? 'dark' : 'light';
  writeThemeCookie(next);
  if (typeof document.startViewTransition === 'function') {
    document.startViewTransition(() => {
      flushSync(() => setMode(nextMode));
    });
    return;
  }
  setMode(nextMode);
};
```

Two pieces are load-bearing and must both be present:

1. **`document.startViewTransition`** captures a pre-state snapshot
   of the page, runs the callback, captures a post-state snapshot,
   and the browser cross-fades the two snapshots as a single GPU
   composite. This replaces N concurrent per-element CSS
   `transition`s on every palette-driven element on screen with one
   GPU layer fade. Browser support: Chromium 111+, Safari 18+,
   Firefox 137+; older browsers fall through to the unwrapped
   `setMode(nextMode)` call below the `if`, where the per-element
   `PALETTE_TRANSITION` overrides on every palette-driven MUI
   styleOverride still produce the fade.

2. **`flushSync`** forces React to commit the `setMode` update
   synchronously inside the View Transitions callback. Without it,
   React batches the update past the post-snapshot capture and the
   View Transition cross-fades two identical snapshots (the post-
   snapshot reflects the *old* DOM because React has not committed
   yet). This is the single most important detail of the wrapping;
   removing it does not throw, it just silently produces a fade
   between identical frames â€” i.e. no visible animation.

Cookie persistence (`writeThemeCookie`) is OUTSIDE the View
Transition callback because it is a synchronous side effect that
should fire regardless of which path runs. localStorage persistence
is INSIDE the callback (implicit through `setMode`) so MUI's
internal mode-storage state stays in lockstep with React's commit.

When adding a new global UI toggle that should cross-fade page-wide
(e.g. a future "compact density" setting), reach for the same
pattern: `document.startViewTransition(() => flushSync(() =>
setX(...)))` with a feature-detection fallback. Do not invent a
new cross-fade primitive.

# CSS variables palette

`frontend/src/theme/buildTheme.js` builds a single static theme via

```js
createTheme({
  cssVariables: { colorSchemeSelector: 'data-mui-color-scheme' },
  colorSchemes: { light: { palette: ... }, dark: { palette: ... } },
});
```

which MUI 7's CSS-variables-aware `<ThemeProvider>` uses to emit
`--mui-palette-*` CSS variables for both schemes and to flip the
active scheme by writing `data-mui-color-scheme` on `<html>`. The
dark/light toggle becomes a CSS-only flip: every element that
references `var(--mui-palette-*)` recomputes styles with no React
re-render. The `useColorScheme()` hook from `@mui/material/styles`
exposes `mode` / `setMode` for the toggle layer.

The `colorSchemeSelector: 'data-mui-color-scheme'` config is
load-bearing and easy to forget. When BOTH `colorSchemes.light`
and `colorSchemes.dark` are defined (as we do), MUI 7 defaults
`colorSchemeSelector` to `'media'`, which gates the per-scheme CSS
variables behind `@media (prefers-color-scheme: ...)` instead of
the data attribute. Under that default our `setMode(...)` call still
writes `data-mui-color-scheme="dark"` on `<html>` and
`useColorScheme().mode` still flips, so the boolean
`darkMode`-driven code paths (mermaid's `theme: darkMode ? 'dark' :
'default'` selection, the per-scheme alpha picks, etc.) continue
to work. The CSS-variable-driven UI, however, stays glued to the OS
theme â€” producing the failure mode "mermaid charts switch theme but
everything else does not", which is harder to diagnose than a
total breakage because half the app appears to work. Always set
`colorSchemeSelector` explicitly to the data-attribute form, and
treat any reappearance of the half-broken symptom as a signal the
config drifted back to `'media'`.

`'true'` is also accepted as a `cssVariables` value (and we used it
briefly during the migration), but the object form with the
explicit selector is the only safe shape now that both schemes are
defined. `'true'` is the same as `{}` and inherits the `'media'`
default.

(MUI 7 deprecated the older `extendTheme` + `CssVarsProvider` pair
in favor of this `createTheme({ cssVariables, colorSchemes })`
pattern; do not regress to the deprecated APIs. The configuration
docs at
https://mui.com/material-ui/customization/css-theme-variables/configuration/
are authoritative.)

Consumers reference palette tokens directly as CSS variable strings
in `sx`:

```js
sx={{
  color: 'var(--mui-palette-text-primary)',
  backgroundColor: 'var(--mui-palette-background-paper)',
}}
```

For alpha composition on a palette token, MUI auto-generates a
`*Channel` variant from the token's `main` value (e.g.
`--mui-palette-highlight-mainChannel` is `12 188 255` for the dark
scheme, `0 151 204` for light). Compose with the standard CSS
`rgba(... / N)` syntax:

```js
sx={{
  borderColor: 'rgba(var(--mui-palette-highlight-mainChannel) / 0.2)',
}}
```

The `*Channel` form intentionally drops any baked-in alpha from the
underlying hex (the dark scheme's `highlightColor` is `#0cbcff8f`,
with ~56% baked alpha), matching the behavior of MUI's `alpha()` JS
utility. For tints whose alpha *value* differs per scheme â€” not just
the underlying color â€” the `darkMode` boolean from
`ThemeModeContext` still picks the alpha at JS time:

```js
backgroundColor: darkMode
  ? 'rgba(var(--mui-palette-highlight-mainChannel) / 0.08)'
  : 'rgba(var(--mui-palette-highlight-mainChannel) / 0.04)',
```

Custom palette tokens (e.g. `highlight`) follow the standard MUI
shape `{ main, light?, dark?, contrastText? }` to get
`*Channel` variants auto-generated; lift any string-typed legacy
field (the original `highlightColor` was a top-level string) into
this shape via a small helper like `paletteFromColors(c)` in
`buildTheme.js` rather than inlining a one-off generator.

Do not introduce a new `useContext(ColorContext)` consumer â€” the
context was deleted by the migration. Read CSS variables from `sx`
directly. The boolean `darkMode` from `ThemeModeContext` is reserved
for the two cases where CSS variables are not enough on their own:

- The alpha value differs per scheme (the example above).
- A non-CSS code path needs the boolean (e.g. mermaid's
  `mermaid.initialize({ theme: darkMode ? 'dark' : 'default' })`
  selection â€” the mermaid library does not read CSS variables, it
  picks a theme name internally).

# Centralize via MUI theme `styleOverrides`

Every palette-driven MUI component carries `transition:
PALETTE_TRANSITION` through `components.<MuiX>.styleOverrides.root`
in `frontend/src/theme/buildTheme.js`. The body fade lives in
`MuiCssBaseline.styleOverrides.body` and is the highest-leverage
entry because `<body>` is the largest visible surface â€” its
`background-color` comes from `theme.palette.background.default` via
MUI's reset.

When a new MUI component is added to the codebase whose default look
is palette-derived (e.g. `MuiAccordion`, `MuiTabs`, `MuiSwitch`),
wire it into the `components` map in the same change. The
transition-only-overrides cluster at the bottom of `buildTheme.js`
(currently `MuiAvatar`, `MuiDivider`, `MuiIconButton`,
`MuiOutlinedInput`, `MuiSvgIcon`, `MuiTypography`) is the canonical
home; alphabetical order within that cluster keeps diffs reviewable.

# Inline `sx` for raw elements

Raw `<Box>` / `<pre>` / `<button>` rendered without a MUI wrapper
that carries `backgroundColor` / `color` / `borderColor` derived
from the palette does **not** pick up the global override and must
opt in via inline `sx`:

```jsx
import { PALETTE_TRANSITION } from '../../theme/transitions';

<Box
  sx={{
    backgroundColor: 'rgba(var(--mui-palette-highlight-mainChannel) / 0.1)',
    transition: PALETTE_TRANSITION,
  }}
/>
```

Canonical sites (consult these before adding new ones):

- `ProjectGroup` inner header `<Box>` â€” the outer `Paper`'s
  `overflow: 'hidden'` clips its own background, so the inner
  `<Box>`'s `background: var(--mui-palette-background-paper)` is
  what users actually perceive as "the chat-categories color block".
- `ChatCard` highlight preview panel `<Box>`.
- `MessageBubble` markdown wrapper `<Box>` and its `'& th'` /
  `'& tr:nth-of-type(even)'` child selectors (see "CSS `transition`
  does not cascade" below).
- `MermaidBlock` outer wrapper, diagram-body
  `<Box component="button">`, and source-mode `<Box component="pre">`.
- `MessageMarkdown` `'& pre'` and `'& :not(pre) > code'` child
  selectors.
- `MessageImageGallery` thumbnail `<Box component="button">`.

# CSS `transition` does not cascade

A parent's `transition` rule does **not** apply to descendant
selectors. When a parent `<Box>` styles children through the MUI
`'& selector'` syntax and those children carry palette-driven
properties, each child selector must carry its own `transition:
PALETTE_TRANSITION`. The motivating site is `MessageBubble.js`'s
`'& th'` and `'& tr:nth-of-type(even)'` rules, both of which set
`backgroundColor: 'rgba(var(--mui-palette-highlight-mainChannel) /
N)'` and would flash if only the parent had a transition.

# SVG content cross-fade (mermaid diagrams)

A CSS `transition` cannot bridge two states when the DOM tree itself
is replaced wholesale on theme toggle. The motivating case is mermaid:
`MermaidBlock` calls `mermaid.render(source)` on every theme flip and
emits a brand-new tree of inline-styled SVG nodes that share no
element identity with the previous render, so every `stroke` /
`fill` / label color flips in a single frame. There is no element
left to transition.

The fix is split between a hook (`useSvgCrossFade` in
`frontend/src/hooks/useSvgCrossFade.js`, which owns the state
machine, the keyframe constant, the gate triple, and the
`onAnimationEnd` cleanup) and its consumer (`MermaidDiagramSurface`
in `frontend/src/components/MermaidDiagramSurface.js`, which owns
the layered JSX and the click-surface plumbing). The hook tracks
the previous SVG string in `useState` and decides via three gates
(visibility, reduced-motion, concurrent-fade cap â€” see below)
whether to mount an outgoing layer; the consumer renders that
layer as an absolutely-positioned `aria-hidden` `<Box>` on top of
the incoming SVG and runs a CSS keyframe animation that fades it
to opacity 0 over `PALETTE_TRANSITION_DURATION` /
`PALETTE_TRANSITION_CURVE`. The hook's `onAnimationEnd` callback
(returned to the consumer, wired into the outgoing layer's
`onAnimationEnd` JSX prop) clears the outgoing slot so the layer
unmounts after the fade completes. Rapid toggles restart the
animation cleanly because the outgoing `<Box>` carries
`key={outgoingSvg}`.

Two implementation choices are load-bearing and must be preserved
in any future similar surface (the hook enforces both):

1. **Detect the prop change during render, not in a `useEffect`.** A
   `useEffect([svg])`-based detection fires after the browser paints,
   which means the user sees one frame of the new SVG with no
   outgoing overlay before the overlay mounts on the next render â€” a
   visible flash that defeats the entire point of the cross-fade.
   React's documented "Storing information from previous renders"
   pattern from the `useState` reference is the right shape: detect
   the change with an inline `if (svg !== committedSvg) { ... }`
   block, call `setState` synchronously to commit the derivation,
   and let React throw away the in-progress render and re-run. Both
   renders happen before the next paint, so the user only ever sees
   the final state with both layers already mounted.
2. **Define the keyframe at module scope via emotion's `keyframes`
   helper, not as an inline `'@keyframes name': { ... }` entry
   inside `sx`.** The inline-in-sx form depends on undocumented
   emotion serialization behavior to install the keyframes rule
   globally and silently fails in some MUI 7 / emotion 11 build
   configurations, leaving the animation property pointing at a name
   no `@keyframes` declaration ever defined. The result is an
   outgoing layer that mounts at `opacity: 1`, never animates, never
   fires `onAnimationEnd`, and stays stuck on top of the incoming
   SVG forever. Importing `keyframes` from `@emotion/react` (the
   approach `useSvgCrossFade` uses) inserts a uniquely-named
   global rule once at module load and returns a token the
   `animation` shorthand interpolates safely. The hook returns the
   pre-composed shorthand string as `fadeAnimation` so the
   consumer drops it into `sx` without re-typing the keyframe
   identifier.

Why a CSS `animation` rather than a `transition` here: a
`transition` only fires when a property changes *after* the element
is in the DOM. The outgoing layer needs to start fading the moment
it mounts (which is the same render in which the incoming SVG
appears). A keyframe animation fires on first paint and runs to
completion regardless, which is the semantic this case needs. Reach
for `PALETTE_TRANSITION_DURATION` + `PALETTE_TRANSITION_CURVE` for
the animation shorthand, never the literal numbers.

Four load-bearing pieces of the cross-fade surface exist purely
for performance, not correctness â€” but if any one is removed the
cross-fade goes from "smooth" to "frame-dropping on long
mermaid-heavy chats". The first three live in `useSvgCrossFade`;
the last is on the consumer's outgoing-layer `sx`:

- **`useInView` gate** (in the hook). The outgoing layer mounts
  only when the consumer's `surfaceRef` element is on-screen. A
  long chat with 30 mermaid blocks where 5 are visible would
  otherwise mount 30 doubled-DOM trees on every theme toggle; the
  gate restricts the cost to the 5 the user can actually see.
- **`useReducedMotion` gate** (in the hook). Stronger than the
  global CSS opt-out in `index.css` (see "Reduced motion" below):
  the CSS rule disables the keyframe animation, but the layer
  would still mount and stick at `opacity: 1` forever (no
  animation â†’ no `onAnimationEnd` â†’ no cleanup). The JS gate
  avoids the mount entirely.
- **`MAX_CONCURRENT_CROSS_FADES` cap** (in the hook). A module-
  scope counter tracks active cross-fades across all
  `useSvgCrossFade` instances; surfaces that would push the count
  past the cap (5 today, heuristic) fall back to instant swap.
  The compositor cost of N concurrent SVG fades scales linearly,
  and beyond ~5 the diminishing return on visual polish stops
  outweighing the frame-time cost. The counter is incremented /
  decremented by a `useEffect([outgoingSvg])` so unmount-mid-fade
  and rapid theme toggles do not leak the counter; React strict-
  mode double-invocation in dev double-invokes the cleanup too,
  so the net delta stays zero.
- **`willChange: 'opacity'` on the outgoing layer** (in the
  consumer's outgoing-layer `sx`, since `sx` for the JSX
  belongs to the consumer). Promotes the layer to its own GPU
  compositor layer for the duration of the fade so alpha
  interpolation runs on the GPU rather than rasterizing the SVG
  every frame. The standard "do not keep `will-change`
  permanently" caveat does not apply because the outgoing layer
  unmounts at animation-end; the lifetime is bounded.

The three gates (visibility, reduced-motion, concurrent-fade cap)
all suppress the *outgoing layer*, never the underlying render â€”
the incoming SVG always updates, only the cross-fade overlay is
conditional. They compose with the View Transitions API at the
page level: View Transitions captures a snapshot of whatever is
in the DOM at flip time, including any in-flight outgoing layers,
so the user sees the page-wide cross-fade and the per-surface
cross-fade as one composite animation.

Two CSS containment hints reduce the layout/paint cost of the
broader page during the fade window. They are the canonical sites
for this pattern; future imperative-DOM components (prism, monaco,
similar) should follow:

- **`contentVisibility: 'auto'` + `containIntrinsicSize: '0 400px'`
  on `MermaidBlock`'s outer `<Box>`.** Tells the browser to skip
  layout and paint of off-screen blocks until they scroll into
  view; the intrinsic-size hint reserves a placeholder height
  (400px is a heuristic for typical mermaid block height) so the
  scrollbar does not jump as off-screen blocks materialize. On
  long chats with many diagrams, this is what keeps the theme
  toggle from re-painting every off-screen SVG subtree.
- **`contain: 'layout paint style'` on `MermaidDiagramSurface`'s
  outer `<Box component="button">`.** Tells the browser the
  surface's layout, paint, and style cannot affect siblings or
  ancestors so it can short-circuit work it would otherwise do
  during the fade (recompute intrinsic dimensions, repaint the SVG
  region, propagate style invalidation up the tree). Safe because
  the lightbox modal is portal-rendered (escapes containment by
  construction) and the cross-fade outgoing layer is `position:
  absolute; inset: 0` already scoped to the button's `position:
  relative`.

- **`data-msg-idx={index}` on `MessageBubble`'s outermost `<Box>`
  (set by `MessageList.map`'s `(message, index)` enumeration).**
  The SAVE half of an anchor-based scroll restoration on chats
  with `content-visibility: auto` blocks: at scroll save time the
  topmost in-viewport bubble is recorded by index plus the user's
  vertical offset within it (`{ msgIdx, offset }` JSON in
  `sessionStorage`), and at restore time the anchor element is
  queried by `[data-msg-idx]` selector so the recomputed
  `targetY = anchor.offsetTop + offset` is layout-independent.
  The legacy plain-number `sessionStorage` format from before
  this change still restores via a `Number(raw)` fallback path.
  Removing the data attribute reduces save/restore to raw
  `scrollY`, which silently drifts the moment any layout-shifting
  placeholder (mermaid 400px, future `content-visibility: auto`
  consumers) lands above the anchor between save and restore.

The RESTORE half pairs the `data-msg-idx` save with a
`requestAnimationFrame`-driven re-scroll loop (capped at 5
iterations) inside the page-level `useLayoutEffect`. The initial
`scrollTo(0, anchor.offsetTop + offset)` is best-effort because it
runs at `scrollY = 0` against a layout where every off-screen
mermaid block is at its 400px placeholder; the
`scrollTo` itself causes the browser to re-evaluate
`content-visibility: auto` for blocks now in or near the new
viewport, materializing them on the next paint and shifting
`anchor.offsetTop` by the cumulative actual-vs-placeholder height
delta -- while `scrollY` stays put. Each rAF iteration re-reads
`document.querySelector('[data-msg-idx="${msgIdx}"]').offsetTop`
and re-`scrollTo`s when the recomputed `offsetTop + offset`
differs from the current `scrollY` by more than a 1-px tolerance
(which prevents a no-op `scrollTo` from re-triggering layout
work). The 5-frame cap is a safety net against pathological
materialization cascades; 2-3 frames are typical in practice.
Skip the loop on the legacy plain-number fallback, the no-saved-
entry case, and the JSON-with-missing-anchor case (a chat that
has lost messages) -- there is no anchor to stabilize against.
Cleanup must `cancelAnimationFrame` the in-flight request so a
component unmount or a navigation to a new `sessionId` does not
keep firing the chain. `ChatDetail.js`'s `useLayoutEffect` is the
canonical site. Removing the rAF loop re-opens the
scroll-drift-on-mermaid-chats bug; removing the `data-msg-idx`
save re-opens the same bug from the SAVE side (raw `scrollY`
becomes layout-dependent again).

This pattern generalizes to any future imperative-DOM library
(prism, monaco, etc.) whose rendered output is not CSS-animatable
across re-renders. Keep the previous output mounted for the fade
duration; do not call the imperative API a second time to "produce
a fade-out copy" â€” that would constitute a third mermaid pipeline
(per [`mermaid-rendering.mdc`](mermaid-rendering.mdc) "Two rendering
pipelines, one source format") and re-open the bomb-graphic risk
closed by the parse-first guard.

# Reduced motion

Users who set `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` at the OS level get
every theme transition and animation disabled. The opt-out is
two-pronged because no single mechanism covers both surfaces:

- A global `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` rule in
  `frontend/src/index.css` overrides `transition: none !important;
  animation: none !important; scroll-behavior: auto !important;` on
  `*, *::before, *::after`. The `!important` is load-bearing: MUI's
  emotion engine generates per-instance class styles with high
  specificity for the inline `sx={{ transition: PALETTE_TRANSITION }}`
  sites and the `MuiX.styleOverrides.root` entries in
  `buildTheme.js`, and an override without `!important` would lose
  the cascade against them. `scroll-behavior: auto` neutralizes any
  future `scroll-behavior: smooth` that might be added (we do not
  set it today, but smooth scrolling is motion the same preference
  asks us to disable, and forgetting it is a documented common bug).
- The `useReducedMotion` hook (`frontend/src/hooks/useReducedMotion.js`)
  gives JS the same signal the CSS rule reads. The canonical
  consumer is `useSvgCrossFade` (called by
  `MermaidDiagramSurface`), where the CSS rule is not enough on
  its own: the keyframe `animation` would be disabled but the
  outgoing layer would still mount and stick at `opacity: 1`
  forever (`onAnimationEnd` never fires when there is no
  animation). The hook's boolean gates the layer mount itself.

The CSS rule covers every other animated surface in the codebase
(every MUI `transition`, every hover bg flip, every scrollbar fade);
the JS hook covers the one place where DOM mounting itself is the
cost. The two are complementary, not redundant.

The View Transitions API path runs independently of
`prefers-reduced-motion`. Browsers honor the preference for the
view-transition cross-fade itself (Chromium auto-disables the
fade when the user requests reduced motion); we do not need a
JS-level gate on `document.startViewTransition`.

Future surfaces that mount DOM specifically for a transition (e.g.
a future cross-fade for prism / monaco / similar imperative-DOM
libraries) should follow the same pattern: gate the mount with
`useReducedMotion` so reduced-motion users do not pay for DOM that
will never animate.

# Modals, dialogs, and context menu are out of scope

Inline `sx` `transition` additions are deliberately omitted from
`ExportFormatDialog`, `ExportWarningDialog`, `ImageLightboxModal`,
`MermaidLightboxModal`, `MermaidLightboxFallback`,
`MermaidZoomControls`, and `AppContextMenu`. These surfaces are
typically closed when the user toggles the theme, so the marginal
polish does not justify the maintenance surface. They still inherit
the centralized transition through the global MUI overrides (Paper,
Button, IconButton, Avatar, Typography, etc.) as a benign side
effect â€” a `Dialog` whose buttons fade is fine, it just isn't
separately decorated.

For `MermaidLightboxModal` specifically there is a substantive
reason to stay out: the modal hosts `useSvgPanZoom`, which writes
`transform: translate(...) scale(...)` to the transform layer on
every pointermove. Adding inline `transition: 'all'` to that layer
or any of its parents would visibly lag the drag. See
[`mermaid-rendering.mdc`](mermaid-rendering.mdc) "Modal pan/zoom/
reset is presentation-only" for the full invariant.

# Scrollbar is the only intentional literal duplicate

`frontend/src/index.css` repeats the literal
`0.2s cubic-bezier(.17,.67,.83,.67)` because CSS cannot import JS
constants. When `PALETTE_TRANSITION` changes, update the three
`transition` rules in `index.css` in the same change. Property
scope on the CSS rules stays narrow (`scrollbar-color` /
`background-color`) rather than `all`: `transition: all` on `<html>`
would animate scroll-induced reflow effects.

The scrollbar's light-mode override selector is
`:root[data-mui-color-scheme="light"]` (matches the attribute
MUI's `<ThemeProvider>` writes), not the legacy
`:root[data-theme="light"]` from before the CSS-variables
migration.

# Cross-reference

This rule is the time-domain extension of
[`react-components.mdc`](react-components.mdc) "Theme ownership":
that rule says MUI theme tokens own *what* color is applied; this
rule says they also own *how* a palette swap unfolds visually. The
two are intentionally separate so a future contributor can violate
one without violating the other (hardcoding a hex breaks Theme
ownership but not this rule; hardcoding a transition curve breaks
this rule but not Theme ownership).
